RP   ERRATUM.
RA   Bond J., Roberts E., Springell K., Lizarraga S.B., Scott S.,
RA   Higgins J., Hampshire D.J., Morrison E.E., Leal G.F., Silva E.O.,
RA   Costa S.M.R., Baralle D., Raponi M., Karbani G., Rashid Y., Jafri H.,
RA   Bennett C., Corry P., Walsh C.A., Woods C.G.;
RL   Nat. Genet. 37:555-555(2005).
CC   -!- FUNCTION: Plays an important role in cell division and centrosome
CC       function by participating in centriole duplication
CC       (PubMed:17681131, PubMed:20531387). Inhibits microtubule
CC       nucleation from the centrosome. Involved in the regulation of slow
CC       processive growth of centriolar microtubules. Acts as microtubule
CC       plus-end tracking protein that stabilizes centriolar microtubules
CC       and inhibits microtubule polymerization and extension from the
CC       distal ends of centrioles (PubMed:15047868, PubMed:27219064,
CC       PubMed:27306797). Required for centriole elongation and for STIL-
CC       mediated centriole amplification (PubMed:22020124). May be
CC       involved in the control of centriolar-microtubule growth by acting
CC       as a regulator of tubulin release (PubMed:27306797).
CC       {ECO:0000269|PubMed:15047868, ECO:0000269|PubMed:17681131,
CC       ECO:0000269|PubMed:20531387, ECO:0000269|PubMed:22020124,
CC       ECO:0000269|PubMed:27219064, ECO:0000305|PubMed:27306797}.
CC   -!- SUBUNIT: Forms homodimers (PubMed:27219064). Associates with
CC       microtubules plus ends; binds to beta-tublin subunits exposed on
CC       microtubule outer surface at its distal tip; also associates with
CC       microtubule lattice (PubMed:19131341, PubMed:27219064,
CC       PubMed:27306797). Associated with the gamma-tubulin complex.
CC       Interacts with the head domain of EPB41 (PubMed:11003675).
CC       Interacts with LYST (PubMed:11984006). Interacts with CEP152 (via
CC       C-terminus) (PubMed:20852615). Interacts with STIL
CC       (PubMed:22020124, PubMed:25385835). Forms a complex with STIL and
CC       SASS6 (PubMed:22020124). {ECO:0000269|PubMed:11003675,
CC       ECO:0000269|PubMed:11984006, ECO:0000269|PubMed:20852615,
CC       ECO:0000269|PubMed:22020124, ECO:0000269|PubMed:25385835,
CC       ECO:0000269|PubMed:27219064, ECO:0000269|PubMed:27306797}.
CC   -!- INTERACTION:
CC       Q66GS9:CEP135; NbExp=8; IntAct=EBI-946194, EBI-1046993;
CC       Q96RK0:CIC; NbExp=2; IntAct=EBI-946194, EBI-945857;
CC       Q5VTD9:GFI1B; NbExp=2; IntAct=EBI-946194, EBI-946212;
CC       Q9NYY3:PLK2; NbExp=3; IntAct=EBI-946194, EBI-721354;
CC       Q15468:STIL; NbExp=13; IntAct=EBI-946194, EBI-7488405;
CC       O95271:TNKS; NbExp=4; IntAct=EBI-946194, EBI-1105254;
CC       P61981:YWHAG; NbExp=3; IntAct=EBI-946194, EBI-359832;
CC   -!- SUBCELLULAR LOCATION: Cytoplasm, cytoskeleton, microtubule
CC       organizing center, centrosome {ECO:0000269|PubMed:11003675,
CC       ECO:0000269|PubMed:20531387}. Cytoplasm, cytoskeleton, microtubule
CC       organizing center, centrosome, centriole
CC       {ECO:0000269|PubMed:17681131, ECO:0000269|PubMed:20531387,
CC       ECO:0000269|PubMed:22020124}. Note=Localized within the center of
CC       microtubule asters (PubMed:11003675). During centriole biogenesis,
CC       it is concentrated within the proximal lumen of both parental
CC       centrioles and procentrioles (PubMed:17681131).
CC       {ECO:0000269|PubMed:11003675, ECO:0000269|PubMed:17681131}.
CC   -!- ALTERNATIVE PRODUCTS:
CC       Event=Alternative splicing; Named isoforms=2;
CC       Name=1;
CC         IsoId=Q9HC77-1; Sequence=Displayed;
CC       Name=2;
CC         IsoId=Q9HC77-2; Sequence=VSP_056831, VSP_056832;
CC         Note=No experimental confirmation available.;
CC   -!- PTM: Phosphorylation at Ser-589 and Ser-595 by PLK2 is required
CC       for procentriole formation and centriole elongation.
CC       Phosphorylation by PLK2 oscillates during the cell cycle: it
CC       increases at G1/S transition and decreases during the exit from
CC       mitosis. Phosphorylation at Ser-595 is also mediated by PLK4 but
CC       is not a critical step in PLK4 function in procentriole assembly.
CC       {ECO:0000269|PubMed:20531387}.
CC   -!- DISEASE: Microcephaly 6, primary, autosomal recessive (MCPH6)
CC       [MIM:608393]: A disease defined as a head circumference more than
CC       3 standard deviations below the age-related mean. Brain weight is
CC       markedly reduced and the cerebral cortex is disproportionately
CC       small. Despite this marked reduction in size, the gyral pattern is
CC       relatively well preserved, with no major abnormality in cortical
CC       architecture. Affected individuals are mentally retarded. Primary
CC       microcephaly is further defined by the absence of other syndromic
CC       features or significant neurological deficits due to degenerative
CC       brain disorder. {ECO:0000269|PubMed:15793586,
CC       ECO:0000269|PubMed:22020124}. Note=The disease is caused by
CC       mutations affecting the gene represented in this entry.
CC   -!- DISEASE: Seckel syndrome 4 (SCKL4) [MIM:613676]: A rare autosomal
CC       recessive disorder characterized by proportionate dwarfism of
CC       prenatal onset associated with low birth weight, growth
CC       retardation, severe microcephaly with a bird-headed like
CC       appearance, and mental retardation. {ECO:0000269|PubMed:20522431}.
CC       Note=The disease is caused by mutations affecting the gene
CC       represented in this entry.
CC   -!- SIMILARITY: Belongs to the TCP10 family. {ECO:0000305}.

CC   -!- FUNCTION: Plays an important role in cell division and centrosome
CC       function by participating in centriole duplication. Inhibits
CC       microtubule nucleation from the centrosome. Involved in the
CC       regulation of slow processive growth of centriolar microtubules.
CC       Acts as microtubule plus-end tracking protein that stabilizes
CC       centriolar microtubules and inhibits microtubule polymerization
CC       and extension from the distal ends of centrioles. Required for
CC       centriole elongation and for STIL-mediated centriole
CC       amplification. May be involved in the control of centriolar-
CC       microtubule growth by acting as a regulator of tubulin release (By
CC       similarity). {ECO:0000250|UniProtKB:Q9HC77}.
CC   -!- SUBUNIT: Forms homodimers. Associates with microtubules plus ends;
CC       binds to beta-tublin subunits exposed on microtubule outer surface
CC       at its distal tip; also associates with microtubule lattice.
CC       Associated with the gamma-tubulin complex. Interacts with the head
CC       domain of EPB41. Interacts with LYST. Interacts with CEP152 (via
CC       C-terminus). Interacts with STIL. Forms a complex with STIL and
CC       SASS6 (By similarity). {ECO:0000250|UniProtKB:Q9HC77}.
CC   -!- SUBCELLULAR LOCATION: Cytoplasm, cytoskeleton, microtubule
CC       organizing center, centrosome {ECO:0000250|UniProtKB:Q9HC77}.
CC       Cytoplasm, cytoskeleton, microtubule organizing center,
CC       centrosome, centriole {ECO:0000250|UniProtKB:Q9HC77}.
CC       Note=Localized within the center of microtubule asters. During
CC       centriole biogenesis, it is concentrated within the proximal lumen
CC       of both parental centrioles and procentrioles (By similarity).
CC       {ECO:0000250|UniProtKB:Q9HC77}.
CC   -!- PTM: Phosphorylation at Ser-577 and Ser-583 by PLK2 is required
CC       for procentriole formation and centriole elongation.
CC       Phosphorylation by PLK2 oscillates during the cell cycle: it
CC       increases at G1/S transition and decreases during the exit from
CC       mitosis. Phosphorylation at Ser-583 is also mediated by PLK4 but
CC       is not a critical step in PLK4 function in procentriole assembly.
CC       {ECO:0000250|UniProtKB:Q9HC77}.
CC   -!- SIMILARITY: Belongs to the TCP10 family. {ECO:0000305}.

ID   CENPJ_PANTR             Reviewed;        1338 AA.
AC   Q5BQN8;
DT   26-APR-2005, integrated into UniProtKB/Swiss-Prot.
DT   12-APR-2005, sequence version 1.
DT   10-MAY-2017, entry version 59.
DE   RecName: Full=Centromere protein J;
DE            Short=CENP-J;
GN   Name=CENPJ;
OS   Pan troglodytes (Chimpanzee).
OC   Eukaryota; Metazoa; Chordata; Craniata; Vertebrata; Euteleostomi;
OC   Mammalia; Eutheria; Euarchontoglires; Primates; Haplorrhini;
OC   Catarrhini; Hominidae; Pan.
OX   NCBI_TaxID=9598;
RN   [1]
RP   NUCLEOTIDE SEQUENCE [MRNA].
RA   Springell K., Bond J., Woods C.G.;
RT   "Chimpanzee CENPJ gene.";
RL   Submitted (FEB-2005) to the EMBL/GenBank/DDBJ databases.
CC   -!- FUNCTION: Plays an important role in cell division and centrosome
CC       function by participating in centriole duplication. Inhibits
CC       microtubule nucleation from the centrosome. Involved in the
CC       regulation of slow processive growth of centriolar microtubules.
CC       Acts as microtubule plus-end tracking protein that stabilizes
CC       centriolar microtubules and inhibits microtubule polymerization
CC       and extension from the distal ends of centrioles. Required for
CC       centriole elongation and for STIL-mediated centriole
CC       amplification. May be involved in the control of centriolar-
CC       microtubule growth by acting as a regulator of tubulin release (By
CC       similarity). {ECO:0000250|UniProtKB:Q9HC77}.
CC   -!- SUBUNIT: Forms homodimers. Associates with microtubules plus ends;
CC       binds to beta-tublin subunits exposed on microtubule outer surface
CC       at its distal tip; also associates with microtubule lattice.
CC       Associated with the gamma-tubulin complex. Interacts with the head
CC       domain of EPB41. Interacts with LYST. Interacts with CEP152 (via
CC       C-terminus). Interacts with STIL. Forms a complex with STIL and
CC       SASS6 (By similarity). {ECO:0000250|UniProtKB:Q9HC77}.
CC   -!- SUBCELLULAR LOCATION: Cytoplasm, cytoskeleton, microtubule
CC       organizing center, centrosome {ECO:0000250|UniProtKB:Q9HC77}.
CC       Cytoplasm, cytoskeleton, microtubule organizing center,
CC       centrosome, centriole {ECO:0000250|UniProtKB:Q9HC77}.
CC       Note=Localized within the center of microtubule asters. During
CC       centriole biogenesis, it is concentrated within the proximal lumen
CC       of both parental centrioles and procentrioles (By similarity).
CC       {ECO:0000250|UniProtKB:Q9HC77}.
CC   -!- PTM: Phosphorylation at Ser-590 and Ser-596 by PLK2 is required
CC       for procentriole formation and centriole elongation.
CC       Phosphorylation by PLK2 oscillates during the cell cycle: it
CC       increases at G1/S transition and decreases during the exit from
CC       mitosis. Phosphorylation at Ser-596 is also mediated by PLK4 but
CC       is not a critical step in PLK4 function in procentriole assembly.
CC       {ECO:0000250|UniProtKB:Q9HC77}.
CC   -!- SIMILARITY: Belongs to the TCP10 family. {ECO:0000305}.

RC   ECO:0000313|Proteomes:UP000006823};
RX   PubMed=21336279; DOI=10.1038/ng.769;
RA   Mitreva M., Jasmer D.P., Zarlenga D.S., Wang Z., Abubucker S.,
RA   Martin J., Taylor C.M., Yin Y., Fulton L., Minx P., Yang S.P.,
RA   Warren W.C., Fulton R.S., Bhonagiri V., Zhang X., Hallsworth-Pepin K.,

RT   "The draft genome of the parasitic nematode Trichinella spiralis.";
RL   Nat. Genet. 43:228-235(2011).
CC   -!- FUNCTION: Core component of nucleosome. Nucleosomes wrap and
CC       compact DNA into chromatin, limiting DNA accessibility to the
CC       cellular machineries which require DNA as a template. Histones
CC       thereby play a central role in transcription regulation, DNA
CC       repair, DNA replication and chromosomal stability. DNA
CC       accessibility is regulated via a complex set of post-translational
CC       modifications of histones, also called histone code, and
CC       nucleosome remodeling. {ECO:0000256|RuleBase:RU000528,
CC       ECO:0000256|SAAS:SAAS00581158}.
CC   -!- SUBUNIT: The nucleosome is a histone octamer containing two
CC       molecules each of H2A, H2B, H3 and H4 assembled in one H3-H4
CC       heterotetramer and two H2A-H2B heterodimers. The octamer wraps
CC       approximately 147 bp of DNA. {ECO:0000256|RuleBase:RU000528,
CC       ECO:0000256|SAAS:SAAS00581166}.
CC   -!- SUBCELLULAR LOCATION: Chromosome {ECO:0000256|SAAS:SAAS00581170}.
CC   -!- SUBCELLULAR LOCATION: Nucleus {ECO:0000256|SAAS:SAAS00581157}.
CC   -!- SIMILARITY: Belongs to the histone H4 family.
CC       {ECO:0000256|RuleBase:RU000528, ECO:0000256|SAAS:SAAS00581172}.
CC   -!- CAUTION: The sequence shown here is derived from an
CC       EMBL/GenBank/DDBJ whole genome shotgun (WGS) entry which is
CC       preliminary data. {ECO:0000313|EMBL:EFV62075.1}.
